━━━ STEP 1: STYLE SELECTION (you must complete this before design) ━━━

Score each of the eight Richards architecture styles against the
inferred characteristics above. Use this catalog:

  1. Layered         — monolithic, technical partitioning, simple
  2. Modular monolith — monolithic, domain partitioning, pragmatic
  3. Microkernel     — monolithic, core + plugins, extensible
  4. Pipeline        — monolithic, filter chain, data processing
  5. Service-based   — distributed, 4-12 coarse services, shared DB
  6. Event-driven    — distributed, async broker/mediator, decoupled
  7. Microservices   — distributed, fine-grained, independent DBs
  8. Space-based     — distributed, in-memory grid, extreme elasticity

For each PRIMARY characteristic, identify which styles it favours
and which it penalises. Sum the scores. Apply the veto rules:

VETO if:
  - Scalability is primary AND team is small → veto microservices
  - Cost or simplicity is primary → veto space-based and microservices
  - Data integrity or consistency is primary → veto event-driven
    and microservices
  - Elasticity primary with > 10x peak → require space-based
    or event-driven only
  - Testability is primary → downgrade event-driven
  - Team has low operational maturity → veto microservices
    and space-based
  - Product with stable core and variable features → require microkernel

If the top two styles are within 3 points, consider a hybrid.
Valid Richards hybrids: event-driven+microservices,
event-driven+service-based, space-based+microservices,
modular monolith → service-based → microservices (evolution path).

Your selected style must be justified with:
  a) which characteristics drove the score
  b) which styles were vetoed and why
  c) why the selected style serves this specific system better
     than the runner-up

